d in East Down (Devon), and three minor places in Devon called Stafford, in Dolton, Broadhembury, and Colyton parishes. The places are all named with Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ as the final element, but have different initial elements. The Staffordshire placename has Old English <i>stæth</i> ‘river bank, shore’; Stafford in Colyton (Devon) has Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’; the Sussex placename has Old English <i>stēor</i> ‘steer, bullock’; East and West Stowford (Devon) have Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’; Stafford in Dolton and Stafford in Broadhembury (Devon) may have Old English <i>stæth</i>, <i>stān</i>, or <i>stæf</i>.","Irish (Wexford): variant of   Stocker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stocker","meanings":["German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>): topographic name for someone living by a tree stump (see   Stock   3) or an occupational name for a tree cutter, from Middle High German <i>stocken</i> ‘to clear land’.","German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>); Dutch: occupational name from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>stocker</i> ‘jailer’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>stokker</i> ‘one who sells stockfish’ (fish dried in the air without salt). This was the usual source of the name in medieval London, where a bylaw of 1419 stated that no <i>stokker</i> should board a ship to buy fish (presumably in order to forestall the market)."]}]},{"name":"Jennet","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a simplified spelling of   Jeannette   or a revival of a medieval pet form of the female name   Jean ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeannette","meanings":["diminutive form of <i>Jeanne</i>, feminine form of <i>Jean</i> ‘John’, now also used in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705208,"age":1,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":14,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":34,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Jennet Stafford was born about 1586, in Kirkheaton, Yorkshire, England. She had at least 5 sons and 3 daughters with Thomas Beaumont. She died about 1641, in England, at the age of 57."},"et":{"abt 1586–abt 1641":"umbes 1586–umbes 1641","1586–1646":"1586–1646","1606–Male":"1606–Surnud","1607–Male":"1607–Surnud","1609–Male":"1609–Surnud","1614–Male":"1614–Surnud","1623–Male":"1623–Surnu